Here's the complete migration:

## Pattern Identified: **Timeout Enforcement**

`Thread.Abort()` forcibly kills the thread on timeout; `Thread.ResetAbort()` suppresses the abort if caught. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`.

---

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must check the CancellationToken for timely cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is OperationCanceledException
                                            && cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Overload preserving the original signature for callers that cannot cooperate.
    /// WARNING: If work ignores the token, it continues running in the background
    /// after timeout ŌĆö there is no way to forcibly stop it in modern .NET.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(work, token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when token fires
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

## Usage Example

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Cooperative (preferred) ŌĆö work checks the token
int result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        // ... do a unit of work ...
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

---

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work ignores the token** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work` never checks the token, it runs to completion in the background even after you throw `TimeoutException`. This is the biggest behavioral difference. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always `using` or `finally`-dispose it. |
| **Blocking calls won't cancel** | `Thread.Sleep`, synchronous I/O, etc. don't check the token. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Let it propagate up the call chain ŌĆö only catch at the orchestration layer. |
| **Fire-and-forget background work** | The non-cooperative overload abandons the task. If `work` holds locks or database transactions, they won't be released until it finishes naturally. |

---

## If Work Truly Cannot Cooperate

For unmodifiable code (e.g., third-party library doing a blocking native call), the only safe option in .NET 8 is **process isolation**:

```csharp
// Move uncooperative work to a child process and kill it on timeout
using var process = Process.Start("WorkerApp.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

This replaces the old `Thread.Abort` semantics with OS-level process termination ŌĆö the only reliable forced-stop mechanism in modern .NET.

---

## What Was Removed

| Old API | Replacement |
|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` (automatic via timeout) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | No equivalent needed ŌĆö check `token.IsCancellationRequested` to decide whether to continue |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `Task.WaitAsync(token)` or `task.Wait(token)` |
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` |
